<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=9678264355613></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9678264355613><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=9678264355613>Your new pet at 34</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=9678264355613#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=1220><span id= >Ursula</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>1 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Sep 1st 12:40 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.71]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>USING YOUR PET IN GROUPS AND WHILE SOLOING <br><br>So you just turned 34 and can't wait to get your puppy. Congratulations! They add a lot of value to the shaman class IF YOU KNOW HOW TO USE THEM. While other classes have spent their last 33 levels getting practice with them, you haven't. And since most of you have been in groups in a dungeon where a pet ran off, died, and caused your whole group to die, I'm sure you don't want to be as unskilled as they were. Anyway, following are some things I've learned. <br><br>Hotkeys <br>It is handy to have your memorised set of combat spells on one set of hotkeys. I have a second with Cannibilise, Sit, Sense Heading, /loc, /corpse, and /gsay "GET THAT MOB OFF ME PLEASE" on it. On a third set of hotkeys, you should have your main attack and pet control keys. This would include: <br>- Melee Attack <br>- /pet back off <br>- /assist <br>- /pet attack <br>- /consider <br>- Sit/Stand <br><br>Soloing that big Mob <br>The big part of soloing the tough mobs is to fully buff yourself and your pet. Note that because they require a lot of prep time, high blue mobs should be avoided if getting lots of experience is your goal. Buff yourself and your pet with SOW, Shifting Shield, Talisman of Tnarg, Strength, and Agility first, then med back to full mana. Cast Quickness and Regenerate on yourself and your pet just before you attack. And remember to put on resistence spells if you are doing casters. Plant your pet somewhere nearby the targetted MOB with /pet guard here, and turn off taunting with /pet no taunt. After that, pull that big mob with Tagor's to your pet. After the pet latches on to him, plant Scourge and your best DOT on the MOB. Your puppy won't be able to survive for long without your help, so whenever the MOB starts picking on him, blast the MOB with Winter's roar till it starts running after you again. After this, start running around in large circles, in 3rd person view mode. Don't get too far away, or the MOB will lose interest in you and target your pet. Remember to reapply the DOT and Scourge when the time comes. <br><br>An alternate plan to kiting is to pull to your pet, and fight it out from there. The advantage is that you will be able to kill them faster because of the running-DOT nerf, but the downside is you will get pounded for a lot of damage. I would recommend this option if you can take the hits. In this case keep the pet taunting so you will be able to back up from the fight occasionally and heal or re-Dot without fear of interruption. <br><br>Grouping in a Dungeon <br>The bottom line to having an effective pet in the dungeons is to keep it from running off, aggrivating a huge pile of MOBs, then training stuff onto you after it dies. Always have the pet assisting the main attacker. If it is on something else, have it /pet back off and retarget it. When you are on a MOB in the dungeon and it starts to run, pets are a mixed blessing. On the up side, it will keep attacking the MOB the entire time until it dies. On the down side, your pet may get attacked by a bunch of MOBs and start fighting all by itself. Once that happens, it is nearly impossible to bring the fight back to where the rest of the group is pulling to. Further, you won't be able to command it since it will be out of speaking range. After the pet dies, all the MOBs that helped to kill your pet will train back to YOU. Therefore, unless there is nothing nearby that will attack your pet, tell it to /pet back off if you get a runner. <br><br>-When grouping with classes that Mezmerise, Sleep or Lull, do a /pet back off just before the MOB dies. Then, after the MOB dies, target your group's main hitter, /assist them, then use /pet attack on the target. There is no evidence from ShowEQ that having the pet do the killing blow steals xp from you. But if you have someone that is Mezzing in your group, this will keep your pet from attacking AND WAKING UP another target that is sleeping after the first one dies. <br><br>-Players using ShowEq claim that you lose 50% of your xp if your pet does over half of the damage. It shouldn't be too tough to outdamage your pet when soloing if you throw in a couple DDs. Signs that your pet is doing over half the damage would be if the MOB keeps on your pet even though you have taunting turned off. <br><br>-Assist ONLY the puller, and only have the pet attack once the MOB has arrived. Enchanters and other classes may be targetting things that you should stay off of. <br><br>-If you are the puller in a group, either don't let the MOBs damage you during a pull or don't keep a pet. The pet will intercept the MOB before its gets back to where your group is, and either die or take the battle to a place where you may not want to fight. <br>&nbsp;<br>-Ursula Winterspirit<br> 52nd Season Shaman<br> Master Alchemist(140)<br> Bristlebane</td></tr>
