<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96716802410505></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96716802410505><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=96716802410505>RE: Depending on level</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=96716802410505#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=492><span id=Sage>Gorthin</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>149 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Aug 24th 9:47 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Well, the concept of not being able to melee beyond a certain point doesn't hold a whole lot of water =)&nbsp;&nbsp;I am a bubb into 37 (Barbarian) and melee to death the mobs I meet.  I can do this with or without a pet.  The pet is just a bonus DoT and safety net.<br>Many have said it before, but I will repeat. Buff yourself. Try to space them so they all do not go away at the same time and you have to eat several hundred mana of rebuffing. Agility for more AC and more misses (152 agi seems to make the mobs miss me about 25% more often), Strength for better chances to hit and better average damage, Inner fire for AC and 20 extra hp, one of the AC lines (whatever you happen to have, turtle skin, shifting shield, etc), the Stamina buff (this sucker adds free hp, not many, but any extra helps), SoW (just in case, hehe), and if you want, quickness if you have it. Med back up to a reasonable amount (I normally go half a bubble short in a dangerous area).  Now, get your slow spell to stick either through multiple recasts or using a malise first (depends on style and how much mana you have to burn).  I personally like to Malise.  Targar's gets resisted a LOT if I don't, and if for some reason I need to root to run or heal, or DD, the Malise helps those get through.  Once slow sticks, time a DoT in between the swings, and melee to you heart's content.  If you get beat on a lot, root, back off and heal if you can't get it through, otherwise, just time the heal.  Pay attention to the kick/bash/strike/extra attack pattern monk and warrior mobs have, and remember to take that extra attack into consideration as to when you try to cast.<br>My typical melee combat goes:  Malise to pull, send pet in if I have him summoned, Slow the mob, Scourge (Disease DoT, melee combats will get you full efficiency out of these), and melee.  Occasionally I will add a Envenomed breath to the mix.  That's it.  I do not nuke, or even heal most of the time during the combat.  The only time I nuke is if the guy is a runner, and it could cause problems, but even then I wait for him to turn and run.  If I did not take very much damage, I will sometimes root the mob when it flees or right before, but if the root breaks, you end up nuking him anyway.<br>Slow spells are the key.  Level 49+ Shamen can solo ice giants because of it.  You can solo all the way there with some patience, although grouping has its merits, too.  <br>If you still find for some reason you are getting beat on too much, then definately either a) join a group or b) learn to root/DoT/med kill.  Either way Shamen are a lot of fun after level 24.<br>Gorthin 37 Shaman Norrathian People's Front Bristlebane<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
